  abstract = {Artificial intelligence (AI) is increasingly shaping political landscapes, with significant implications for democracy. As generative AI technologies become more integrated into governance and political communication, concerns have emerged regarding the potential of using them to undermine democratic processes and institutions. This paper investigates into these concerns and maps how generative AI technologies are used by different actors with the intention to weaken democratic governments by leveraging a three-step approach. First, and based on recent literature, we conceptualize six different types of AI-powered threats to democratic principles, processes, and institutions. Second, we make use of the large language models gemma3 and gpt-4o-mini to assess the scope and intensity of these AI-powered threats in individual countries (2023-2024). Third, based on manual checks and an expert survey we validate and improve the quality of this newly created dataset. We then use the novel data and variables from the V-Dem project to investigate into the drivers and effects of AI-powered threats to democracy. We find that while most countries are not yet heavily affected by AI-powered threats to democracy, some of these risks are particularly high during election years when political actors are most interested in shaping the public discourse and influencing electoral outcomes. We also find that the risks of AI-powered threats to democracy are higher in countries with lower levels of democracy and that regulatory frameworks play a crucial role in mitigating these risks and their negative effects on election quality.},
